Section.Description: This section summarizes the environmental fate/exposure of this chemical, including the natural and artificial sources of the chemical as a pollutant, its environmental fate, biodegradation, abiotic degradation, bioconcentration, etc.

StringWithMarkup.String: 2-Undecanone's production may result in its release to the environment through various waste streams; it's use as a solvent in the production of vinyl resins, nitrocellulose and synthetic rubber, a dog and cat repellent and as a fragrance additive to soaps, detergents, creams, lotions and perfume will result in its direct release to the environment. If released to air, a vapor pressure of 4.1X10-2 mm Hg at 25 °C indicates 2-undecanone will exist solely as a vapor in the atmosphere. Vapor-phase 2-undecanone will be degraded in the atmosphere by reaction with photochemically-produced hydroxyl radicals; the half-life for this reaction in air is estimated to be 1.2 days. If released to soil, 2-undecanone is expected to have moderate mobility based upon a Koc of 280. Volatilization from moist soil surfaces may be an important fate process based upon a Henry's Law constant of 6.36X10-5 atm-cu m/mole. 2-Undecanone is not expected to volatilize from dry soil surfaces based upon its vapor pressure. 2-undecanone is expected to biodegrade under aerobic conditions in the soil and water. If released into water, 2-undecanone is not expected to adsorb to suspended solids and sediment based upon the Koc. Volatilization from water surfaces may be an important fate process based upon this compound's Henry's Law constant. Estimated volatilization half-lives for a model river and model lake are 13 hours and 11 days, respectively. An estimated BCF of 28 suggests the potential for bioconcentration in aquatic organisms is low. Occupational exposure to 2-undecanone may occur through dermal contact with this compound at workplaces where 2-undecanone is produced or used. Monitoring data indicate that the general population may be exposed to 2-undecanone via inhalation of ambient air, ingestion of food and drinking water, and dermal contact with this compound and other consumer products containing 2-undecanone. Section.Description: Sorption to soils and sediments is an important factor on the transport and fate of organic contaminants in the environment.  The soil/water adsorption coefficient, also known as solid-water distribution coefficient (Kd), measures the amount of chemical substance adsorbed onto soil per amount of water. The greater the Kd (or Koc) value, the less likely a chemical will leach or contribute to runoff.  A very high value means it is strongly adsorbed onto soil and organic matter and does not move throughout the soil.
